PhysicalQuantity.Name: ELECTRICAL_ENERGY
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: The amount of electricity used or stored. The base unit used in NMEA 2000 is the Kilo Watt Hour (kWh) which is equivalent to 3.6e6 J (Joules).

PhysicalQuantity.Name: ELECTRICAL_POWER
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: The amount of energy transferred or converted per unit time.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: ELECTRICAL_APPARENT_POWER
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: The amount of power transferred where the current and voltage are in phase.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: ELECTRICAL_REACTIVE_POWER
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: The amount of power transferred where the current and voltage are not in phase.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: POWER_FACTOR
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: Used in AC circuits only, the ratio of the real power absorbed by the load to the apparent power flowing in the circuit. If less than one, the voltage and current are not in phase.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: LENGTH
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: The physical size in one dimension of an object.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: DISTANCE
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: The amount of separation between two objects.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: SPEED
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: The velocity, or length per unit of time.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: ANGLE
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: All standardized PGNs seen so far all use radians, but some manufacturer specific PGNs use degrees (deg).

PhysicalQuantity.Name: ANGULAR_VELOCITY
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: The speed at which a measured angle changes

PhysicalQuantity.Name: VOLUME
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: A measure of occupied three-dimensional space.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: VOLUMETRIC_FLOW
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: The volume of fluid which passes per unit time.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: DATE
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: A calendar date is a reference to a particular day in time, in NMEA 2000 expressed as the number of days since 1970-01-01 (UNIX epoch).

PhysicalQuantity.Name: TIME
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: Time is what clocks measure. We use time to place events in sequence one after the other, and we use time to compare how long events last. Absolute times in NMEA2000 are expressed as seconds since midnight(in an undefined timezone)

PhysicalQuantity.Name: DURATION
PhysicalQuantity.Description: Duration of an event or interval between two points in time

PhysicalQuantity.Name: GEOGRAPHICAL_LATITUDE
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: Combined with a geographical longitude the two fields form a unique point on earth, when height is disregarded.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: GEOGRAPHICAL_LONGITUDE
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: Combined with a geographical latitude the two fields form a unique point on earth, when height is disregarded.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: PRESSURE_RATE
PhysicalQuantity.Comment: How the pressure changes over time.

PhysicalQuantity.Name: CONCENTRATION
PhysicalQuantity.Description: Concentration of one substance in another, in this marine context usually the amount of salts in water

PhysicalQuantity.Name: SIGNAL_STRENGTH
PhysicalQuantity.Description: Signal strength expressed in dB with respect to 1 uV/m

FieldType.Name: NUMBER
FieldType.EncodingDescription: Binary numbers are little endian. Number fields that are at least two bits in length use the highest positive value to represent unknown. Number fields with at least 7 as maximum (3 bits unsigned, 4 bits signed) use the highest value minus one as an error indicator. This is likely also true for numbers where 3 is the maximum value, but there are few fields that have this length -- certainly as a number, there are a lot of lookup fields of two bits length. For signed numbers the maximum values are the maximum positive value and that minus 1, not the all-ones bit encoding which is the maximum negative value.

FieldType.Name: DECIMAL
FieldType.Description: A unsigned numeric value represented with 2 decimal digits per byte
FieldType.EncodingDescription: Each byte represent 2 digits, so 1234 is represented by 2 bytes containing 0x12 and 0x34. A number with an odd number of digits will have 0 as the first digit in the first byte.

FieldType.Name: LOOKUP
FieldType.Description: Number value where each value encodes for a distinct meaning
FieldType.EncodingDescription: Each lookup has a LookupEnumeration defining what the possible values mean
FieldType.Comment: For almost all lookups the list of values is known with some precision, but it is quite possible that a value occurs that has no corresponding textual explanation. Generally the same special values for Error (max value - 1) and Unknown (max value) that are used for plain numbers are also valid for lookups, but some lookups define a lookup key/value pair for the maximum possible value in that field. In fact, recent additions to PGNs such as alerts have two bit lookup fields that specify four actual valid values. This makes it impossible to send an unknown value for these fields.

FieldType.Name: INDIRECT_LOOKUP
FieldType.Description: Number value where each value encodes for a distinct meaning but the meaning also depends on the value in another field
FieldType.EncodingDescription: Each lookup has a LookupIndirectEnumeration defining what the possible values mean
FieldType.Comment: For almost all lookups the list of values is known with some precision, but it is quite possible that a value occurs that has no corresponding textual explanation.

FieldType.Name: BITLOOKUP
FieldType.Description: Number value where each bit value encodes for a distinct meaning
FieldType.EncodingDescription: Each LookupBit has a LookupBitEnumeration defining what the possible values mean. A bitfield can have any combination of bits set.
FieldType.Comment: For almost all lookups the list of values is known with some precision, but it is quite possible that a value occurs that has no corresponding textual explanation.

FieldType.Name: DYNAMIC_FIELD_KEY
FieldType.Description: Number value where each value encodes for a distinct meaning including a fieldtype of the next variable field; generally followed by an optional DYNAMIC_FIELD_LENGTH and a DYNAMIC_FIELD_VALUE field; when there is no DYNAMIC_FIELD_LENGTH field the length is contained in the lookup table
FieldType.EncodingDescription: Each lookup has a LookupFieldTypeEnumeration defining what the possible values mean
FieldType.Comment: These values have been determined by reverse engineering, given the known values it is anticipated that there are unkown enumeration values and some known values have incorrect datatypes

FieldType.Name: DYNAMIC_FIELD_LENGTH
FieldType.Description: Number value that indicates the length of the following DYNAMIC_FIELD_VALUE field

FieldType.Name: DYNAMIC_FIELD_VALUE
FieldType.Description: Variable field whose type and length is dynamic
FieldType.EncodingDescription: The type definition of the field is defined by an earlier LookupFieldTypeEnumeration field. The length is defined by the preceding length field or the length determined by the lookup value.

FieldType.Name: DATE
FieldType.EncodingDescription: The date, in days since 1 January 1970.

FieldType.Name: PGN
FieldType.EncodingDescription: A 24 bit number referring to a PGN

FieldType.Name: ISO_NAME
FieldType.EncodingDescription: A 64 bit field containing the ISO name, e.g. all fields produced by PGN 60928. Use the definition of PGN 60928 to explain the subfields.

FieldType.Name: STRING_FIX
FieldType.Description: A fixed length string containing single byte codepoints.
FieldType.EncodingDescription: The length of the string is determined by the PGN field definition. Trailing bytes have been observed as '@', ' ', 0x0 or 0xff.
FieldType.Comment: It is unclear what character sets are allowed/supported. Possibly UTF-8 but it could also be that only ASCII values are supported.

FieldType.Name: STRING_LZ
FieldType.Description: A varying length string containing single byte codepoints encoded with a length byte and terminating zero.
FieldType.EncodingDescription: The length of the string is determined by a starting length byte. It also contains a terminating zero byte. The length byte includes neither the zero byte or itself. The character encoding is UTF-8.
FieldType.Comment: This type of string is found only in SonicHub and Fusion brand specific PGNs. SonicHub is no longer produced. The use of the Fusion specific PGNs is no longer very prevalent now that there are generic PGNs for audio/media devices.

FieldType.Name: STRING_LAU
FieldType.Description: A varying length string containing double or single byte codepoints encoded with a length byte and terminating zero.
FieldType.EncodingDescription: The length of the string is determined by a starting length byte. This count includes the length and type bytes, so any empty string contains count 2. The 2nd byte contains 0 for UNICODE or 1 for ASCII.

FieldType.Name: BINARY
FieldType.EncodingDescription: Unspecified content consisting of any number of bits.

FieldType.Name: RESERVED
FieldType.Comment: NMEA reserved for future expansion and/or to align next data on byte boundary

FieldType.Name: SPARE
FieldType.Comment: This is like a reserved field but originates from other sources where unused fields shall be 0, like the AIS ITU-1371 standard.

FieldType.Name: MMSI
FieldType.EncodingDescription: The MMSI is encoded as a 32 bit number, but is always printed as a 9 digit number and should be considered as a string. The first three or four digits are special, see the USCG link for a detailed explanation.

FieldType.Name: VARIABLE
FieldType.EncodingDescription: The definition of the field is that of the reference PGN and reference field, this is totally variable.

FieldType.Name: FIELD_INDEX
FieldType.EncodingDescription: Index of the specified field in the PGN referenced.

This message is provided by ISO 11783 for a handshake mechanism between transmitting and receiving devices. This message is the possible response to acknowledge the reception of a 'normal broadcast' message or the response to a specific command to indicate compliance or failure.

Field.Name: PGN
Field.Description: Parameter Group Number of requested information

PGNInfo.Explanation: As defined by ISO, this message has a data length of 3 bytes with no padding added to complete the single frame. The appropriate response to this message is based on the PGN being requested, and whether the receiver supports the requested PGN.
ISO 11783 defines this PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN represents a single packet of a multipacket message.

Field.Name: Data
Field.Description: Multi-packet packetized data - 56 bits organized as seven 8-bit bytes, each of the bytes is transmitted in the same order as it would in a standard (i.e., single frame) message. Unused bytes shall be filled with 0xFF.

PGNInfo.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - Request To Send
PGNInfo.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to prepare the receiver for the fact that this sender wants to transmit a long message. The receiver will respond with CTS.

Field.Name: Packets reply
Field.Description: packets sent in response to CTS

PGNInfo.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - Clear To Send
PGNInfo.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to signal to the sender that the receive is ready to receive a number of frames.

Field.Name: Max packets
Field.Description: Number of frames that can be sent before another CTS is required

Field.Name: Next SID
Field.Description: Number of next frame to be transmitted

PGNInfo.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - End Of Message
PGNInfo.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to mark the end of the message.

Field.Name: Total number of frames received
Field.Description: Total number of of frames received

PGNInfo.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - Broadcast Announce
PGNInfo.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to announce a broadcast of a long message spanning multiple frames.

PGNInfo.Description: ISO Transport Protocol, Connection Management - Abort
PGNInfo.Explanation: ISO 11783 defines this group function PGN as part of the Transport Protocol method used for transmitting messages that have 9 or more data bytes. This PGN's role in the transport process is to announce an abort of a long message spanning multiple frames.

Field.Name: SID

PGNInfo.Explanation: Reception of this PGN confirms that a device is still present on the network. Reception of this PGN may also be used to maintain an address to NAME association table within the receiving device. The transmission interval may be used by the receiving unit to determine the time-out value for the connection supervision. The value contained in Field 1 of this PGN reflects the PGN's current Transmission Interval. Changes to this PGN's Transmission Interval shall be reflected in Field 1. The transmission interval can only be changed by using the Request Group Function PGN 126208 with no pairs of request parameters provided. Field 3 of the Request Group Function PGN 126208 may contain values between 1,000ms and 60,000ms. This PGN cannot be requested by the ISO Request PGN 059904 or Request Group Function PGN 126208. In Request Group Function PGN 126208, setting Field 3 to a value of 0xFFFF FFFF and Field 4 to a value of 0xFFFF: 'Transmit now without changing timing variables.' is prohibited. The Command Group Function PGN 126208 shall not be used with this PGN. Fields 3 and 4 of this PGN provide information which can be used to distinguish short duration disturbances from permanent failures. See ISO 11898 -1 Sections 6.12, 6.13, 6.14, 13.1.1, 13.1.4, 13.1.4.3 and Figure 16 ( node status transition diagram) for additional context.

The MOB PGN is intended to provide notification from a MOB monitoring system. The included position information may be that of the vessel or the MOB device itself as identified in field 'X', position source. Additional information may include the current state of the MOB device, time of activation, and MOB device battery status. This PGN may be used to set a MOB waypoint, or to initiate an alert process. This PGN may be used to command or register a MOB device emitter Ids or other applicable fields in the message with an MOB System or other equipment. If the fields in this PGN are configured over the network, the Command Group Function (PGN 126208) shall be used. Queries for this PGN shall be requested using either the ISO Request (PGN 059904) or the NMEA Request Group Function (PGN 126208). A device receiving an ISO (PGN 059904) for this PGN (127233), shall respond by providing as many of these PGNs (127233) as necessary for every MOB Emitter ID that has associated data fields. If a Request Group Function (PGN 126208) requesting this PGN (127233) is received, the receiving device shall respond in the following manner: * If no requested fields have been included with the Request Group Function then the response is to return one or more PGNs, just like responding to the ISO Request (PGN 055904) described above. * If the Request Group Function (PGN 126208) includes the MOB Emitter ID field or MOB Status field, then the response shall be filtered by these fields contained within this request resulting in one or more PGN (127233) responses. If the MOB Emitter ID requested is not considered a valid MOB Emitter ID by the receiving device, then the appropriate response would be the Acknowledge Group Function (PGN 126208), containing the error state for PGN error code (Field 3) of '0x3 = Access denied.' And the requested MOB Emitter ID field parameter error code (Field 6) of '0x3 = Requested or command parameter out-of- range;'. The Default update rate of this PGN is autonomous, as it is dependant upon notification rates of MOB devices.

Field.Name: MOB Emitter ID

PGNInfo.Explanation: Actuator is a broad description of any device that embodies moving an object between two fixed limits, such as raising or lowering an outboard engine assembly. In the context of this PGN, the word "Device" refers to the object being moved. In the case of multiple Actuators per controller, the Actuator Identifier field specifies which Actuator the PGN message is intended for, and all following data fields refer only to that Actuator. This PGN supports manufacturer calibrated systems and retrofit systems where it is impractical for the installer to enter the Maximum Travel distance of the device.

PGNInfo.Explanation: The Radio Channel is NOT a numeric field, it has been observed to contain values such as 9000L1-L3 and 9000F1-F3 (indicating private channels as allowed in some countries.)

Field.Name: Radio Channel
Field.Description: MF/HF telephone channels to have first digit 3 followed by ITU channel numbers with leading zeros as required. MF/HF teletype channels to have first digit 4; the send and third digit give the frequency bads; and the fourth to sixth digits ITU channel numbers; each with leading zeros as required. VHF channels to have the first digit 9 followed by zero. The next digit is 1 indicating the ship stations transmit frequency is being used as a simplex channel frequency, or 2 indicating the cost stations transmit frequency is being used as a simplex channel frequency, 0 otherwise. THe remaining three numbers are the VHF channel numbers with leading zeros as required.

This PGN provides a lighting controller settings and number of supported capabilities.
This PGN is used to report or configure a name for a given zone. A zone is a grouping of devices that are controlled by a Scene. This PGN is only sent upon request.
A Lighting Scene is a sequence of zone program configurations.
This PGN is used to provide status and capabilities of a lighting device. A lighting device may be a virtual device connected to a lighting controller or physical device on the network.
This PGN allows for enumeration of the lighting devices on the controller.
Sequences could be 1 to (PGN Lighting - System Configuration) Max Color Sequence Color Count colors.
This PGN describes an available program on the controller. Can be a built in required NMEA one or a custom vendor program.
